      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Structural Movement and Cracking: What Brisbane Sellers Must Know Before Listing
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Cracks in a Brisbane home are not all equal. Some are cosmetic. Some are structural. And some are a material fact that must be disclosed before you go to market.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Cracking in a Brisbane home is one of those issues that exists on a spectrum, and the important skill for sellers is understanding where their property sits on that spectrum before their buyer's building inspector makes that determination for them. Fine hairline cracks in plaster walls are normal. They result from the slight movement every timber-framed house makes over decades of seasonal change, and they are not, on their own, a material defect or a disclosure obligation. What sits at the other end of the spectrum is different: wide diagonal cracks, step cracking in brick veneer, cracks at the corners of door and window openings, and cracks that have been filled multiple times because they reopen with the seasons. Those are structural movement indicators, and if you are aware of them, you have a disclosure obligation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why Brisbane's soils make this more common here</h2>
      <p>Brisbane's inner east sits predominantly on reactive clay soils. These soils are expansive: they absorb water and swell when wet, then shrink and contract when they dry out. Every wet season and dry season, the soil beneath footings and slabs goes through this cycle, and the footings move with it. Most of the time this movement is minor and uniform, and the building moves as a whole without distress. The problem arises when movement is not uniform: when one corner of a slab settles more than another, or when the soil under one section of footing dries out faster than the rest. This differential settlement is what produces the structural cracking patterns that indicate a problem.</p>

      <p>In Brisbane's inner east, properties built between the 1950s and 1980s on concrete slab or brick pier footings are the most commonly affected. The construction methods of that era often did not account adequately for the reactive behaviour of the clay soils, and many of these homes have experienced some degree of differential settlement over their lifetime. That does not mean they are unsafe or unsaleable. It means that sellers of these properties need to understand what their building is doing and be prepared to disclose it accurately.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The difference between cosmetic and structural cracking</h2>
      <p>Cosmetic cracking includes hairline cracks in plaster or render that run in relatively straight lines, surface cracks that are less than 1-2 millimetres wide, and cracks that appear in the same locations season after season without widening. These are normal and do not typically affect the structural integrity of the building or its market value. Most buyers expect to see them in an older home and they are readily repaired with plaster filler before or during a pre-sale preparation program.</p>

      <p>Structural cracking looks and behaves differently. Wide diagonal cracks running at 45 degrees from the corners of openings, step cracking that follows the mortar joints in brickwork, cracks that are wider at one end than the other, cracks that were filled previously and have reopened, and cracking accompanied by sticking doors or out-of-square windows are all indicators of differential movement in the structure. These should not be filled and painted over and left undisclosed. A competent building inspector will identify them and the buyer will want to understand what they are dealing with.</p>

      <p>There is also a specific scenario worth understanding: subsidence. This is where soil movement causes footings to sink unevenly, leading to structural distortion in the frame above. Subsidence can occur following a drought that has dried and shrunk the clay well below normal depth, or following changes to drainage patterns around the property. It tends to produce a distinct pattern of cracking concentrated around the most affected structural element, and it is not something that resolves on its own without remediation of the footing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What underpinning means and why it must be disclosed</h2>
      <p>Underpinning is the process of re-supporting a footing that has moved or is at risk of further movement. It typically involves drilling concrete piers or installing steel driven piles beneath or adjacent to the existing footing and transferring the footing load to a more stable depth below the active clay zone. Underpinning is an effective remediation for subsidence, and properties that have been properly underpinned by a licensed structural engineer can perform well and sell without issue. But they must be disclosed.</p>

      <p>If your property has been underpinned, you are required to disclose that fact to prospective buyers. Underpinning is evidence that the footing experienced significant movement, and buyers have a legitimate interest in understanding that history. The disclosure should include when the underpinning was carried out, who did it, and whether a structural engineer's sign-off was obtained. If you have the engineer's report and the contractor's documentation, make them available to your agent for disclosure to buyers. This transparency gives buyers confidence that the issue was properly addressed by professionals, rather than leaving them to form their own assessment of an undisclosed footing history.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How building inspectors assess structural movement</h2>
      <p>A thorough building inspector assessing an older Brisbane property will look specifically for evidence of differential movement. They will check doors and windows for operation: doors and windows that bind, stick, or are visibly out of square are a primary indicator of frame distortion. They will inspect the subfloor on a lowset home, looking at the condition of piers, bearers, and joists and checking for evidence of past movement or repair. They will assess the crack patterns in walls and ceilings, noting the direction, width, and distribution of cracks. They will look for evidence of past remediation: filled and repainted cracks, replaced sections of wall lining, documentation of underpinning in the subfloor or on the exterior of the building.</p>

      <p>In short: if structural movement has occurred, a diligent inspector will find evidence of it. There is no reliable way to conceal structural movement history from a competent building inspection. Sellers who understand this and disclose proactively are in a far better position than those who try to present the property as though no movement has occurred and are then confronted with a detailed report during a conditional buying period.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do before listing if you know there is a structural issue</h2>
      <p>If you are aware of structural movement or cracking in your property, the recommended path before listing is to engage a structural engineer for an assessment and report. An engineer will tell you whether the movement is ongoing or historical, whether remediation is required, and what the appropriate scope of works would be. That report gives you a factual basis for disclosure and, if remediation is carried out, documentation of what was done and by whom.</p>

      <p>Sellers who know there is a structural issue and choose to disclose it alongside an engineer's report and contractor documentation are presenting the situation in the strongest possible way. A buyer who sees a problem, a professional assessment of it, and evidence that it was competently remediated has the information they need to make a confident decision. That is a much more manageable situation than a buyer who discovers an undisclosed structural issue through their own inspector and is now uncertain about everything else in the property as well.</p>

      <p>Where remediation is not feasible before the campaign, the appropriate response is disclosure and accurate pricing. Properties with known structural issues can and do sell, but they need to be priced to reflect the cost and uncertainty the buyer is accepting. Attempting to achieve a price that assumes no structural issues on a property that has them is the scenario most likely to lead to a failed sale, a re-price, or post-settlement legal action.</p>

